        <h2>History</h2>
        <p>The name Avalon first appeared in Geoffrey of Monmouth's Historia Regum Britanniae (c. 1136), where it is described as the island where Arthur was taken for healing. In his Vita Merlini (c. 1150), he further describes it as the "Island of Apples"</p>
        <h2>Symbolism</h2>
        <p>Avalon represents a place of magic, utopia, and healing, often symbolizing a transition between the mortal world and the mystical realm. It also plays a crucial role in the Arthurian legend as the place where Arthur's sword, Excalibur, was forged and where he was taken for his final rest.</p> 
